Dynamic property names are a nightmare (are there any rules regarding the key names?). You should aim for a structure like this:
```
[
   {
      &quot;key&quot;: &quot;key1&quot;
      &quot;value&quot;: &quot;value1&quot;
   },
   {
      &quot;key&quot;: &quot;key2&quot;
      &quot;value&quot;: &quot;value2&quot;
   },
   {
      &quot;key&quot;: &quot;key3&quot;
      &quot;value&quot;: &quot;value3&quot;
   }
]
```

You could archieve this by altering the input json string to match said structure. Then passing it into a normal json parser.

You can also use `List` to deserialize it, then cast all retrieved items to `Map`. This is possible, because Jackson will internally deserialize each array element as a `Map` (as a generic fallback). 

```java
List&lt;?&gt; list = objectMapper.readValue(new File(&quot;1.json&quot;), List.class);
// assuming there exists an item
Map&lt;?,?&gt; item1 = list.get(0);
// .. use map with dynamic keys (you known values are strings, so cast)
String value1 = (String) map.get(&quot;key1&quot;);
``` 

For a huge JSON array it would be rather ineffective (as it would create a huge number of singleton maps). So, solution proposed by @Eskapone (if you can alter the schema of input JSON) is better in these cases.

